# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: open-redirect-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] This article lists standard and notable non-standard HTTP response status codes.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Standardized codes are defined by IETF as documented in Request for Comments (RFC) publications and maintained by the IANA.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Other, non-standard values are used by various servers.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The descriptive text after the numeric code – the *reason phrase* – is shown here with typical value, but in practice, can be different or omitted.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Status codes defined by IETF are listed below.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Emphasized terms *must*, *must not* and *should* are interpretation guidelines as given by RFC 2119.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] An informational response indicates that the request was received and understood and is being processed.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] It alerts the client to wait for a final response.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] As the HTTP/1.0 standard did not define any 1xx status codes, servers *must not* send a 1xx response to an HTTP/1.0 compliant client except under experimental conditions.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Sending a large request body to a server after a request has been rejected for inappropriate headers would be inefficient.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] status code in response before sending the body.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] If the client receives an error code such as 403 (Forbidden) or 405 (Method Not Allowed) then it should not send the request's body.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] header as it indicates that the server does not support expectations (this is the case, for example, of HTTP/1.0 servers).
