[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A WebDAV request may contain many sub-requests involving file operations, requiring a long time to complete the request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] This code indicates that the server has received and is processing the request, but no response is available yet.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] This prevents the client from timing out and assuming the request was lost.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Used to return some response headers before final HTTP message.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A success status indicates that the action requested by the client was received, understood, and accepted.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Standard response for successful HTTP requests.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] In a GET request, the response will contain an entity corresponding to the requested resource.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] In a POST request, the response will contain an entity describing or containing the result of the action.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The request has been fulfilled, resulting in the creation of a new resource.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The request might or might not be eventually acted upon, and may be disallowed when processing occurs.
