[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The range header is used by HTTP clients to enable resuming of interrupted downloads, or split a download into multiple simultaneous streams.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] message and can contain a number of separate response codes, depending on how many sub-requests were made.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The members of a DAV binding have already been enumerated in a preceding part of the (multistatus) response, and are not being included again.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The server has fulfilled a request for the resource, and the response is a representation of the result of one or more instance-manipulations applied to the current instance.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A 3xx status indicates that the client must take additional action, generally URL redirection, to complete the request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A user agent may carry out the additional action with no user interaction if the method used in the additional request is GET or HEAD.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A user agent should prevent cyclical redirects.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] If a client has link-editing capabilities, it should update references to the request URL.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The response is cacheable unless indicated otherwise.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Except for a GET request, the body should contain a hyperlink to the new URL(s).
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Except for a GET or HEAD request, the client must ask the user before redirecting.
