[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] When complete, the response may contain this status code and a redirect URI to the final result.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] In such case, there is no need to retransmit the resource since the client still has a previously-downloaded copy.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The requested resource is available only through a proxy, the address for which is provided in the response.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] In this case, the request should be repeated with another URI; however, future requests should still use the original URI.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] In contrast to how 302 was historically implemented, the request method is not allowed to be changed when reissuing the original request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] For example, a POST request should be repeated using another POST request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] So, for example, submitting a form to a permanently redirected resource may continue smoothly.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A 4xx status code is for situations in which an error seems to have been caused by the client.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Except when responding to a HEAD request, the server *should* include an entity containing an explanation of the error situation, and whether it is a temporary or permanent condition.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] These status codes are applicable to any request method.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] User agents *should* display any included entity to the user.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The server cannot or will not process the request due to an apparent client error (e.g., malformed request syntax, size too large, invalid request message framing, or deceptive request routing).
