[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Indicates that the resource requested was previously in use but is no longer available and will not be available again.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] This should be used when a resource has been intentionally removed and the resource should be purged.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Upon receiving a 410 status code, the client should not request the resource in the future.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Clients such as search engines should remove the resource from their indices.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Most use cases do not require clients and search engines to purge the resource, and a "404 Not Found" may be used instead.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The request did not specify the length of its content, which is required by the requested resource.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The server does not meet one of the preconditions that the requester put on the request header fields.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The request is larger than the server is willing or able to process.
