[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The following codes are used by various web servers but not specified by an IETF standard.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Microsoft's Internet Information Services (IIS) web server expands the 4xx error space to signal errors with the client's request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] IIS sometimes uses additional decimal sub-codes for more specific information, however these sub-codes only appear in the response payload and in documentation, not in the place of an actual HTTP status code.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The client's session has expired and must log in again.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The server cannot honor the request because the user has not provided the required information.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Indicates that Windows Parental Controls block access to the requested webpage.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] when either a more efficient server is available or the server cannot access the users' mailbox.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The client is expected to re-run the HTTP AutoDiscover operation to find a more appropriate server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The nginx web server software expands the 4xx error space to signal issues with the client's request.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] to instruct the server to return no information to the client and close the connection immediately.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Client sent too large request or too long header line.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] response code, used when a client certificate is required but not provided.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] response code, used when the client has made a HTTP request to a port listening for HTTPS requests.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Used when the client has closed the request before the server could send a response.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare's reverse proxy service expands the 5xx series of errors space to signal issues with the origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The origin server returned an empty, unknown, or unexpected response to Cloudflare.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The origin server refused connections from Cloudflare.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Security solutions at the origin may be blocking legitimate connections from certain Cloudflare IP addresses.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare timed out contacting the origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare could not contact the origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare was able to complete a TCP connection to the origin server, but the origin did not provide a timely HTTP response.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare could not validate the SSL certificate on the origin web server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Error 527 indicated an interrupted connection between Cloudflare and the origin server's Railgun server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] This error is obsolete as Cloudflare has deprecated Railgun.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Cloudflare was unable to resolve the origin hostname, preventing it from establishing a connection to the origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The body of the response contains an 1xxx error.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Amazon Web Services' Elastic Load Balancing adds a few custom return codes to signal issues either with the client request or with the origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Returned with an HTTP/2 GOAWAY frame if the compressed length of any of the headers exceeds 8K bytes or if more than 10K requests are served through one connection.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Client closed the connection with the load balancer before the idle timeout period elapsed.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Typically, when client timeout is sooner than the Elastic Load Balancer's timeout.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The load balancer received an X-Forwarded-For request header with more than 30 IP addresses.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] Incompatible protocol versions between Client and Origin server.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] An error around authentication returned by a server registered with a load balancer.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] A listener rule is configured to authenticate users, but the identity provider (IdP) returned an error code when authenticating the user.
[src:open-redirect-defense/http-302] The server has exceeded the bandwidth specified by the server administrator; this is often used by shared hosting providers to limit the bandwidth of customers.
